text: So by nature of being a multi-factor quantitative shop, we're generally looking for slower signals, much higher breadth. But you really see alternative data sources running the gamut of being available to other types of investors, people that are looking for a very high breadth but fast signal. A Stadar firm, for example, really being able to jump in on some of that sentiment, understanding social media feeds, understanding news, and trading intraday on that information. You've got the opposite side of it being a very low breadth but fast signal where an event-driven shop can use information. For example, one of the cool things I've heard is people tracking corporate jet movements to try to predict M&A activity, watching where one executive is flying to another if I know where company headquarters are located, looking at viewing habits. What are people watching on Netflix? What's the new latest blockbuster that's come out on HBO, et cetera, that tends to be a little bit more niche but very impactful on a company? Perhaps some of my favorite examples being in that low breadth, slow signal space as well. So you'll see activist investors, private equity, venture capital, real estate, sometimes being really interested in some of these very narrow, maybe it only covers one or two stocks, but that's general. And then you'll see people who are just fine. So real estate developers or somebody that invests in REITs looking at foot traffic, for example, at airports or at shopping malls, understanding where people are moving around, spending their time. There was a lot of interest for a while before Uber and Lyft went public of keeping tabs on which company was winning out in the ride share world, who was getting market share from whom, and using alternative data to get an insight into that. Also seeing some of this start to spread over to the fixed income world where people are saying, can I use some of this data to get a heads up on credit as well? So a lot of different applications that are out there for alternative data, not necessarily just the stuff that we're looking for.
